  <title>The lazy singleton pattern revisited.</title>
  <description />
  <content>&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you want to get a feel for the singleton pattern in C# one of the best resources I always revisit is on John Skeet&amp;rsquo;s (@jonskeet) website&amp;nbsp; &lt;a href="http://www.yoda.arachsys.com/csharp/singleton.html"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #0066cc;"&gt;http://www.yoda.arachsys.com/csharp/singleton.html&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I encourage you to read the above article to appreciate the little intricacies or requiring static constructor, BeforeFieldInit, volatile etc.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However: If you just want the easiest lazy evaluation solution in .net4+, then you&amp;rsquo;ve come to the right place.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="./image.axd?picture=image_230.png"&gt;&lt;img style="background-image: none; padding-top: 0px; padding-left: 0px; display: inline; padding-right: 0px; border-width: 0px;" title="image" src="./image.axd?picture=image_thumb_230.png" alt="image" width="711" height="508" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Lazy&amp;lt;T&amp;gt; guarantees thread-safe lazy construction.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;&lt;span style="color: #ff0000;"&gt;UPDATE: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If I&amp;rsquo;d followed Jon&amp;rsquo;s notice, at the top of the page I linked to, I would have seen the post is now located &lt;a href="http://csharpindepth.com/Articles/General/Singleton.aspx" target="_blank"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; and moreover, he covers the Lazy&amp;lt;T&amp;gt; approach there.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
